Well, otherwise I guess he
would have been bored to death.

00:23:13.790 --> 00:23:15.500
If you're Bob Dylan,
you've been doing

00:23:15.500 --> 00:23:17.520
the same thing for 40 years.

00:23:17.520 --> 00:23:19.910
You don't want to
play the same songs.

00:23:19.910 --> 00:23:21.140
It goes out of your ears.

00:23:21.140 --> 00:23:23.699
Your ears will explode if you
hear that song one more time.

00:23:23.699 --> 00:23:24.240
I don't know.

00:23:24.240 --> 00:23:24.990
I'm not Bob Dylan.

00:23:24.990 --> 00:23:28.490
But I guess that's what
was going on in his mind.

00:23:28.490 --> 00:23:30.290
You need to try new things.

00:23:30.290 --> 00:23:32.270
You need to push the boundaries.

00:23:32.270 --> 00:23:35.900
Most people, when you ask
them how can you reach best

00:23:35.900 --> 00:23:39.290
performance, they say this
happens when the challenge

00:23:39.290 --> 00:23:41.450
meets your skill set.

00:23:41.450 --> 00:23:42.840
No, that's not true.

00:23:42.840 --> 00:23:46.610
This happens when the challenge
exceeds your skill set.

00:23:46.610 --> 00:23:50.960
You need to be slightly
over-challenged.

00:23:50.960 --> 00:23:54.080
Find a job you really love
and then push yourself

00:23:54.080 --> 00:23:55.190
to the boundaries.

00:23:55.190 --> 00:23:56.210
Get over the top.

00:23:56.210 --> 00:23:59.240
Do things that are a bit
too difficult for you.

00:23:59.240 --> 00:24:01.460
Do things that are a bit scary.

00:24:01.460 --> 00:24:03.140
If you're never
scared at your job,

00:24:03.140 --> 00:24:04.850
something's wrong with you.

00:24:04.850 --> 00:24:06.575
You need to be
sometimes a bit nervous.

00:24:06.575 --> 00:24:08.750
You need to try new things.

00:24:08.750 --> 00:24:10.190
You need to experiment.

00:24:10.190 --> 00:24:12.800
If you're always staying
in your comfort zone,

00:24:12.800 --> 00:24:15.890
your brain will react by
going into your basal ganglia.

00:24:15.890 --> 00:24:19.100
Because when we have a
slight level of fear,

00:24:19.100 --> 00:24:23.000
our brain releases a substance
called noradrenaline.

00:24:23.000 --> 00:24:28.970
And noradrenaline is a
positive stress hormone.

00:24:28.970 --> 00:24:29.990
OK?

00:24:29.990 --> 00:24:33.960
Noradrenaline-- might not
be the prettiest flip chart

00:24:33.960 --> 00:24:37.160
you guys have seen.

00:24:37.160 --> 00:24:40.250
So here it is for those of
you who want to write it down.

00:24:40.250 --> 00:24:42.020
So you need the dopamine.

00:24:42.020 --> 00:24:43.696
But you also need
the noradrenaline.

00:24:43.696 --> 00:24:45.320
When there's no
challenge, when there's

00:24:45.320 --> 00:24:48.770
no deadline, when nobody
cares about what you're doing,

00:24:48.770 --> 00:24:50.390
you will under-perform.

00:24:50.390 --> 00:24:52.580
You will go into
basal ganglia mode.

00:24:52.580 --> 00:24:53.900
So push yourself.

00:24:53.900 --> 00:24:56.060
If you find yourself too
comfortable in your role,

00:24:56.060 --> 00:24:59.960
you might want to quit your
job or go on a job rotation

00:24:59.960 --> 00:25:01.940
or try something new.

00:25:01.940 --> 00:25:03.470
If you're getting
too comfortable,

00:25:03.470 --> 00:25:05.390
you will go into boreout.

00:25:05.390 --> 00:25:08.150
And your brain will
think, why should I

00:25:08.150 --> 00:25:10.220
engage my prefrontal cortex?

00:25:10.220 --> 00:25:12.920
It costs me a lot of
energy and attention

00:25:12.920 --> 00:25:14.870
to engage my prefrontal cortex.

00:25:14.870 --> 00:25:18.590
The brain will only do it
when it's really necessary.

00:25:18.590 --> 00:25:21.800
And if there is no challenge,
if there's no fear,

00:25:21.800 --> 00:25:24.570
your brain will not go
through all of this effort.

00:25:24.570 --> 00:25:28.220
So you need to be slightly
over-challenged to achieve

00:25:28.220 --> 00:25:30.730
that.

00:25:30.730 --> 00:25:32.590
Yes, a question?

00:25:32.590 --> 00:25:35.500
AUDIENCE: Regarding the fear
and the stress, well, I'm not

00:25:35.500 --> 00:25:37.510
an expert in this issue at all.

00:25:37.510 --> 00:25:44.470
But that hormone is a good
one when we are a bit nervous

00:25:44.470 --> 00:25:45.680
or with fear.

00:25:45.680 --> 00:25:48.830
But is it associated
also with cortisol,

00:25:48.830 --> 00:25:50.530
like it happens
at the same time?

00:25:50.530 --> 00:25:52.840
And is it-- because I've
heard that cortisol is not

00:25:52.840 --> 00:25:54.740
that good for your performance.

00:25:54.740 --> 00:25:56.757
So then I would like to know--

00:25:57.257 --> 00:25:57.730
FRIEDERIKE FABRITIUS:
Mhm, the difference.

00:25:57.730 --> 00:25:59.380
AUDIENCE: --your
opinion about it.

00:25:59.380 --> 00:26:00.505
FRIEDERIKE FABRITIUS: Yeah.

00:26:00.505 --> 00:26:02.510
Cortisol is also helpful.

00:26:02.510 --> 00:26:03.700
But it's not a good thing.

00:26:03.700 --> 00:26:06.190
Cortisol is a negative
stress hormone.

00:26:06.190 --> 00:26:08.380
So what happens with
cortisol is that if you

00:26:08.380 --> 00:26:12.010
have that over a longer
period of time in your body,

00:26:12.010 --> 00:26:14.170
you will go into burnout.

00:26:14.170 --> 00:26:16.430
A part of your brain
called the amygdala,

00:26:16.430 --> 00:26:19.420
which is processing negative
information, will grow.

00:26:19.420 --> 00:26:21.820
Your prefrontal
cortex will shrink.

00:26:21.820 --> 00:26:24.820
Your hippocampus for
learning will shrink as well.

00:26:24.820 --> 00:26:29.270
So cortisol has a very
damaging impact on our brain.

00:26:29.270 --> 00:26:31.180
But when is cortisol released?

00:26:31.180 --> 00:26:36.520
Cortisol is released when
there's chronic stress

00:26:36.520 --> 00:26:38.390
over a longer period of time.

00:26:38.390 --> 00:26:42.160
So let's say you have an awful
boss who treats you badly.

00:26:42.160 --> 00:26:45.010
If you live in a
dysfunctional relationship,

00:26:45.010 --> 00:26:47.050
if you go to your
job every morning

00:26:47.050 --> 00:26:49.389
and you feel that
you hate it, that

00:26:49.389 --> 00:26:50.805
will give you a
level of cortisol.

00:26:50.805 --> 00:26:52.750
And when you feel so
overstressed that you

00:26:52.750 --> 00:26:55.000
can't sleep anymore,
it's the cortisol

00:26:55.000 --> 00:26:57.100
hindering you to go to sleep.

00:26:57.100 --> 00:27:00.520
Noradrenaline gives
you positive push, OK?

00:27:00.520 --> 00:27:01.810
So it gives you a kick.

00:27:01.810 --> 00:27:05.380
Cortisol will slow
things down for you.

00:27:05.380 --> 00:27:08.770
So this is the matter of whether
it's a short-term stress--

00:27:08.770 --> 00:27:10.810
here, I am speaking
about short-term stress,

00:27:10.810 --> 00:27:12.190
which is good--

00:27:12.190 --> 00:27:14.170
or whether it's a
long-term stress.

00:27:14.170 --> 00:27:18.560
And then the number one
protection factor for cortisol

00:27:18.560 --> 00:27:20.620
is actually autonomy.

00:27:20.620 --> 00:27:24.370
If you think about it, big
bosses in large organizations,

00:27:24.370 --> 00:27:26.140
they work many hours.

00:27:26.140 --> 00:27:27.970
But they're not as
stressed as the people

00:27:27.970 --> 00:27:30.520
at the bottom, who
maybe work 9:00 to 5:00.

00:27:30.520 --> 00:27:33.760
Because when we can
influence the situation,

00:27:33.760 --> 00:27:36.670
that's when our brain makes
sense of the situation.

00:27:36.670 --> 00:27:40.150
It does matter whether
you work up to 3:00 AM

00:27:40.150 --> 00:27:42.340
because your boss
told you to do that

00:27:42.340 --> 00:27:45.310
or whether you work up to 3:00
AM because it's your company,

00:27:45.310 --> 00:27:47.740
and you chose to do that,
if you feel that there's

00:27:47.740 --> 00:27:49.490
a purpose associated with it.

00:27:49.490 --> 00:27:51.370
So if you want to
avoid cortisol,

00:27:51.370 --> 00:27:54.910
try to take as much control
of the situation as you can.

00:27:54.910 --> 00:27:57.820
Rather than being a victim,
go into a more active role

00:27:57.820 --> 00:28:00.270
to fight the situation.

00:28:00.270 --> 00:28:01.600
OK?

00:28:01.600 --> 00:28:05.330
So that's the noradrenaline
and the fear part.

00:28:05.330 --> 00:28:07.270
What about focus?

00:28:07.270 --> 00:28:14.200
Imagine some athlete in
the middle of a match,

00:28:14.200 --> 00:28:15.700
like Johnny Sexton.

00:28:15.700 --> 00:28:19.570
Or imagine Serena Williams
playing a tennis match.

00:28:19.570 --> 00:28:21.430
And then in the
middle of the match,

00:28:21.430 --> 00:28:23.040
she's pulling out
her cell phone.

00:28:23.040 --> 00:28:24.820
She says, I just need
to take that call.

00:28:24.820 --> 00:28:25.660
Hold on a moment.

00:28:25.660 --> 00:28:27.730
Or I need to check my emails.

00:28:27.730 --> 00:28:29.260
People would hate that.

00:28:29.260 --> 00:28:30.730
Their friends would be appalled.

00:28:30.730 --> 00:28:32.320
People would be shocked.

00:28:32.320 --> 00:28:33.790
But in the business
world, that's

00:28:33.790 --> 00:28:36.910
how people behave all
the time, constantly.

00:28:36.910 --> 00:28:38.890
People are multitasking.

00:28:38.890 --> 00:28:41.920
People are constantly
checking their emails.

00:28:41.920 --> 00:28:45.610
People are hardly
ever focused, right?

00:28:45.610 --> 00:28:49.240
And research shows
that when we multitask,

00:28:49.240 --> 00:28:52.330
we make 50% more mistakes.

00:28:52.330 --> 00:28:56.050
And we take 50% longer
to complete the task.

00:28:56.050 --> 00:28:58.360
Research also shows
that today's teenagers

00:28:58.360 --> 00:29:00.640
have the attention span
shorter than the one

00:29:00.640 --> 00:29:02.800
of an average goldfish.

00:29:02.800 --> 00:29:04.420
Attention span is going down.

00:29:04.420 --> 00:29:05.800
Our brains are plastic.

00:29:05.800 --> 00:29:07.670
We're adapting to
new situations.

00:29:07.670 --> 00:29:09.550
And if you're
constantly multitasking,

00:29:09.550 --> 00:29:11.080
you're not getting better at it.

00:29:11.080 --> 00:29:12.940
Your attention span is
actually going down.

00:29:12.940 --> 00:29:16.090
Because your brain says, I
never need focused, prolonged

00:29:16.090 --> 00:29:17.080
attention, right?

00:29:17.080 --> 00:29:17.770
I never need it.

00:29:17.770 --> 00:29:20.020
So why should I
develop that skill?

00:29:20.020 --> 00:29:22.760
But it's impossible to
reach peak performance

00:29:22.760 --> 00:29:24.610
if you're not fully focused.

00:29:24.610 --> 00:29:28.090
Because when you're
fully focused and present

00:29:28.090 --> 00:29:30.970
in the moment, your brain
will release a substance

00:29:30.970 --> 00:29:33.560
called acetylcholine.

00:29:33.560 --> 00:29:35.470
Let me write it
down here for you.

00:29:42.220 --> 00:29:44.920
As we saw in that little
exercise we did in the group

00:29:44.920 --> 00:29:50.050
this morning, you really had to
focus on keeping the seven out

00:29:50.050 --> 00:29:51.230
of the game, right?

00:29:51.230 --> 00:29:53.860
You really had to focus on
these complex calculations.

00:29:53.860 --> 00:29:57.070
Your prefrontal cortex will only
work when you're fully focused.

00:29:57.070 --> 00:29:58.780
It requires attention.

00:29:58.780 --> 00:30:02.740
It's impossible to get into
flow if you're not focused.

00:30:02.740 --> 00:30:04.540
So what should you do about it?

00:30:04.540 --> 00:30:05.990
I mean, there's many ways to go.

00:30:05.990 --> 00:30:08.710
One of them is, for example,
to eliminate distractions

00:30:08.710 --> 00:30:09.820
from the onset.

00:30:09.820 --> 00:30:13.270
Because our prefrontal
cortex is a limited resource.

00:30:13.270 --> 00:30:16.900
If you are going to spend all
of your energy suppressing

00:30:16.900 --> 00:30:19.750
the urge to check your phone--
let's say it's on your desk

00:30:19.750 --> 00:30:21.280
while you work on something.

00:30:21.280 --> 00:30:23.680
And then you just read
a book that told you

00:30:23.680 --> 00:30:24.957
that multitasking is bad.

00:30:24.957 --> 00:30:26.540
And then you decided
to check it less.

00:30:26.540 --> 00:30:28.581
You're always going to
look at and think, no, OK.

00:30:28.581 --> 00:30:29.500
I check it later.

00:30:29.500 --> 00:30:30.111
Get rid of it.

00:30:30.111 --> 00:30:30.610
OK?

00:30:30.610 --> 00:30:32.180
Put it somewhere else.

00:30:32.180 --> 00:30:34.850
I know that many
executives are now

00:30:34.850 --> 00:30:38.020
doing what is called
a meeting of one.

00:30:38.020 --> 00:30:39.850
When we get in a meeting
with other people,

00:30:39.850 --> 00:30:41.290
we always schedule time.

00:30:41.290 --> 00:30:43.310
We turn off the phone.

00:30:43.310 --> 00:30:46.690
We don't check-- you know, we
really focus on that meeting.

00:30:46.690 --> 00:30:54.550
But you should be just
as critical, rigorous,

00:30:54.550 --> 00:30:56.170
when you have a
meeting with yourself.

00:30:56.170 --> 00:30:58.630
If you really have to put
an important presentation

00:30:58.630 --> 00:31:02.080
together, if you really have
to solve an important question,

00:31:02.080 --> 00:31:03.060
take some time.

00:31:03.060 --> 00:31:04.450
Block your door.

00:31:04.450 --> 00:31:06.250
Don't let people walk in on you.

00:31:06.250 --> 00:31:08.650
You know, I don't know if you
have an open office policy

00:31:08.650 --> 00:31:10.240
or something like this.

00:31:10.240 --> 00:31:13.040
Put something in front of your
door so that nobody can get in.

00:31:13.040 --> 00:31:14.410
It's nice to be social.

00:31:14.410 --> 00:31:16.870
But research shows that
when people have too much

00:31:16.870 --> 00:31:19.930
open office spaces,
collaboration and communication

00:31:19.930 --> 00:31:21.550
actually decreases.

00:31:21.550 --> 00:31:22.820
You think it would go up.

00:31:22.820 --> 00:31:26.170
But it actually goes down,
because people are hiding.

00:31:26.170 --> 00:31:28.870
Because it's impossible to
focus if you constantly have

00:31:28.870 --> 00:31:30.220
your colleagues in your ear.

00:31:30.220 --> 00:31:32.650
So find a way to truly
focus on your work.

00:31:32.650 --> 00:31:37.300
But I would like to let
you in on a little secret.

00:31:37.300 --> 00:31:42.100
Most books will tell you
that eliminating distraction

00:31:42.100 --> 00:31:43.840
is the right way
to improve focus,

00:31:43.840 --> 00:31:46.870
or that you should go to a
mindfulness training course

00:31:46.870 --> 00:31:51.240
and learn meditation and do
yoga, something to train up

00:31:51.240 --> 00:31:53.680
your inherent ability to focus.

00:31:53.680 --> 00:31:54.760
That's good.

00:31:54.760 --> 00:31:56.650
But it's not really
working, because people

00:31:56.650 --> 00:31:58.930
know that multitasking is bad.

00:31:58.930 --> 00:32:00.700
And they keep doing it anyhow.

00:32:00.700 --> 00:32:02.620
Why do they keep
doing it anyhow?

00:32:02.620 --> 00:32:05.230
Because we're addicted
to our phones.

00:32:05.230 --> 00:32:07.030
If you think about
it, every time

00:32:07.030 --> 00:32:10.802
you get a new email or something
happens through social media,

00:32:10.802 --> 00:32:12.760
your brain thinks, oh,
there could be something

00:32:12.760 --> 00:32:14.110
new and relevant going on.

00:32:14.110 --> 00:32:15.290
I need to check that out.

00:32:15.290 --> 00:32:17.170
And then you get a
burst of dopamine.

00:32:17.170 --> 00:32:18.820
And you get a burst
of noradrenaline

00:32:18.820 --> 00:32:21.560
because there could be
something relevant for you.

00:32:21.560 --> 00:32:26.770
And when we are bored at
work and tired and a bit,

00:32:26.770 --> 00:32:30.340
you know, not fully motivated,
you might just as well

00:32:30.340 --> 00:32:33.850
pick up your phone to see
if something new is going on

00:32:33.850 --> 00:32:36.820
in order to get a quick
burst of dopamine.

00:32:36.820 --> 00:32:41.260
Or when you're very
stressed and you

00:32:41.260 --> 00:32:43.020
want to escape from
that situation,

00:32:43.020 --> 00:32:45.200
your phone could be
an escape strategy.

00:32:45.200 --> 00:32:47.490
Rather than focusing on
what's going on around you,

00:32:47.490 --> 00:32:49.300
you focus on your phone.

00:32:49.300 --> 00:32:51.850
And what happens is that every
time a new email comes up

00:32:51.850 --> 00:32:54.910
or something new happens, you
get these bursts of dopamine.

00:32:54.910 --> 00:32:57.460
And they link in to the
reward circuit in your brain.

00:32:57.460 --> 00:32:59.050
And you get addicted to it.

00:32:59.050 --> 00:33:01.240
And you need more
and more and more.

00:33:01.240 --> 00:33:04.750
As you can see in teenagers,
drug use has gone down,

00:33:04.750 --> 00:33:06.680
but phone use has gone up.

00:33:06.680 --> 00:33:07.690
So it's the new drug.

00:33:07.690 --> 00:33:13.030
Basically, in the brain,
multitasking and the use

00:33:13.030 --> 00:33:16.129
of mobile devices is
treated like an addiction.

00:33:16.129 --> 00:33:17.920
If you look at people's
brain while they're

00:33:17.920 --> 00:33:21.370
looking at their phone, it's
like a brain love or a brain

00:33:21.370 --> 00:33:22.780
on drugs.

00:33:22.780 --> 00:33:29.080
So I want to invite you to
create a work environment that

00:33:29.080 --> 00:33:32.590
is more fun and where you
have the right level of fear.

00:33:32.590 --> 00:33:35.680
And then focus will
come naturally.

00:33:35.680 --> 00:33:37.280
Pay attention to that.

00:33:37.280 --> 00:33:40.790
You will see that these things
are correlated to each other.

00:33:40.790 --> 00:33:43.720
When you have fun at work and
when there's truly something

00:33:43.720 --> 00:33:46.810
at stake, when it's
challenging, your focus

00:33:46.810 --> 00:33:48.580
will be there immediately.

00:33:48.580 --> 00:33:51.110
Yesterday, I had a
session with executives.

00:33:51.110 --> 00:33:53.320
And they were working on glass.

00:33:53.320 --> 00:33:55.150
We first wanted
to do a fire walk.

00:33:55.150 --> 00:33:57.970
But then the university
building wouldn't allow that.

00:33:57.970 --> 00:34:01.250
So then we did a
glass walk on real--

00:34:01.250 --> 00:34:04.210
you know, it was 70 bottles
of glass, shattered,

00:34:04.210 --> 00:34:06.760
70 bottles of wine,
shattered on the floor.

00:34:06.760 --> 00:34:10.370
And people were walking
over it barefoot.

00:34:10.370 --> 00:34:12.830
Nobody was multitasking
while doing that.

00:34:12.830 --> 00:34:14.960
Everybody was focused.

00:34:14.960 --> 00:34:15.650
Trust me.

00:34:15.650 --> 00:34:16.570
I've seen people.

00:34:16.570 --> 00:34:19.790
Everybody was really paying
attention while walking,

00:34:19.790 --> 00:34:22.110
because you don't
want to hurt yourself.

00:34:22.110 --> 00:34:23.969
So you have a certain
level of fear.

00:34:23.969 --> 00:34:27.199
And it was kind of fun, because
it was new and unexpected,

00:34:27.199 --> 00:34:29.750
not something you
do every day, right?

00:34:29.750 --> 00:34:31.710
Oh, let's walk on glass today.

00:34:31.710 --> 00:34:33.350
So people had fun.

00:34:33.350 --> 00:34:34.250
People had fear.

00:34:34.250 --> 00:34:36.616
And everybody was focused.

00:34:36.616 --> 00:34:38.449
We didn't even have to
tell people to focus.

00:34:38.449 --> 00:34:39.770
Focus just happened.

00:34:39.770 --> 00:34:42.710
So if you find yourself
having trouble with focus,

00:34:42.710 --> 00:34:45.830
improve the level of fun,
improve the level of fear.

00:34:45.830 --> 00:34:48.170
And it will come naturally.

00:34:48.170 --> 00:34:49.281
Thank you.

