00:36:15.355 --> 00:36:16.480
AUDIENCE: Definitely, yeah.

00:36:16.480 --> 00:36:16.890
That, I agree.

00:36:16.890 --> 00:36:17.390
FRIEDERIKE FABRITIUS: Right.

00:36:17.390 --> 00:36:19.530
I agree with you that
in the moment when

00:36:19.530 --> 00:36:21.360
you play the video
game, you are in flow.

00:36:21.360 --> 00:36:22.140
You have the fun.

00:36:22.140 --> 00:36:22.890
You have the fear.

00:36:22.890 --> 00:36:24.460
You have the focus for sure.

00:36:24.460 --> 00:36:26.610
But if you do
things that give you

00:36:26.610 --> 00:36:28.660
no gratification
in the beginning,

00:36:28.660 --> 00:36:31.200
such as learning to
play an instrument

00:36:31.200 --> 00:36:35.850
or reading long books
with more than 100 pages,

00:36:35.850 --> 00:36:39.030
right, then what happens
is that your brain

00:36:39.030 --> 00:36:42.100
will get used to not get
everything right away.

00:36:42.100 --> 00:36:44.070
But a lot of it has
to do with parenting.

00:36:44.070 --> 00:36:46.980
If your parents brought
you up to work for things,

00:36:46.980 --> 00:36:49.380
then you probably will continue
to do that later in life

00:36:49.380 --> 00:36:49.810
as well.

00:36:49.810 --> 00:36:51.185
So when you have
kids, you should

00:36:51.185 --> 00:36:53.880
be thinking about not
spoiling them too much,

00:36:53.880 --> 00:36:57.510
or they will not have that
ability to delay gratification.

00:36:57.510 --> 00:36:59.820
And then you have
what we see today,

00:36:59.820 --> 00:37:03.690
that many millennials are
having suicidal thoughts

00:37:03.690 --> 00:37:06.600
and are very unhappy because
they always got everything

00:37:06.600 --> 00:37:07.440
from their parents.

00:37:07.440 --> 00:37:10.870
They never had to
work to get anything.

00:37:10.870 --> 00:37:13.140
AUDIENCE: So you were
talking about the correlation

00:37:13.140 --> 00:37:14.650
between performance and stress.

00:37:14.650 --> 00:37:17.820
So if you were to look at
it in a perspective of time

00:37:17.820 --> 00:37:21.400
as well, because for me, that
dopamine and the noradrenaline

00:37:21.400 --> 00:37:23.100
and all of the fun,
fear, and focus

00:37:23.100 --> 00:37:25.950
seems to be a little
bit more short-term.

00:37:25.950 --> 00:37:27.120
Is that true?

00:37:27.120 --> 00:37:29.794
Or how long can you
keep going like that?

00:37:29.794 --> 00:37:31.710
FRIEDERIKE FABRITIUS:
It's a short-term thing.

00:37:31.710 --> 00:37:33.900
You cannot be all day in flow.

00:37:33.900 --> 00:37:35.850
And you shouldn't
be all day in flow.

00:37:35.850 --> 00:37:38.250
Because if you think about
it, when your brain releases

00:37:38.250 --> 00:37:41.040
dopamine and noradrenaline
and acetylcholine,

00:37:41.040 --> 00:37:43.080
it gives your brain
a quick burst.

00:37:43.080 --> 00:37:45.270
But then it vanishes quickly.

00:37:45.270 --> 00:37:47.250
If you think about
negative stress

00:37:47.250 --> 00:37:50.020
hormones, such as cortisol,
they hit your body.

00:37:50.020 --> 00:37:51.780
And they can stay forever.

00:37:51.780 --> 00:37:56.340
Let's say I give you 10
things to think about.

00:37:56.340 --> 00:37:57.990
I say, you did great
and this and this

00:37:57.990 --> 00:37:59.940
and this and this
and this and this,

00:37:59.940 --> 00:38:03.720
and great job at this, and
great, and great, hooray.

00:38:03.720 --> 00:38:06.060
And then I say you have one
little area for improvement,

00:38:06.060 --> 00:38:07.664
one little thing to work on.

00:38:07.664 --> 00:38:09.330
That's the one you're
going to remember.

00:38:09.330 --> 00:38:13.140
We are wired to focus
on negative things.

00:38:13.140 --> 00:38:13.800
OK?

00:38:13.800 --> 00:38:17.130
So what this means is that
this is a short-term thing.

00:38:17.130 --> 00:38:20.520
You should use that if
you want to get something

00:38:20.520 --> 00:38:22.440
really important done.

00:38:22.440 --> 00:38:24.780
And then it's OK to
spend the rest of the day

00:38:24.780 --> 00:38:28.080
sometimes under-challenged,
sometimes over-challenged.

00:38:28.080 --> 00:38:30.120
This is something you
should use for your most

00:38:30.120 --> 00:38:31.540
important moments.

00:38:31.540 --> 00:38:33.120
If you think about
athletes, they

00:38:33.120 --> 00:38:35.520
spend a week training
and recovering.

00:38:35.520 --> 00:38:37.690
And then they just
have a one-hour match.

00:38:37.690 --> 00:38:39.480
You need that for
that one-hour match.

00:38:39.480 --> 00:38:41.820
And afterwards, your
brain will be depleted.

00:38:41.820 --> 00:38:45.690
What you see is that when
your brain releases dopamine,

00:38:45.690 --> 00:38:47.610
when all of that
dopamine is used up,

00:38:47.610 --> 00:38:50.980
you feel kind of
like, whew, exhausted.

00:38:50.980 --> 00:38:53.200
So it's a short-term thing.

